Executing the Effective Empirical Modeling Methodology (EEM-M) in R

Takaki Hayashi

2023-12-25 (Preliminary version)

In this document, we introduce our R functions that enable data analysts to execute EEM-M in R. Specifically, we explain the main functions setenv() and run_eem() and their usage with concrete examples. (Note: ATTOW, the package is yet to be ready for distribution. Specifications of the functions can be modified through time.) The Shiny app EEM-M has been written based on these functions.

Necessary packages (dependencies)

library(tidyverse)

1 Gasoline consumption data (Chatterjee and Hadi, 2012)

As an illustration, we use the Gasoline consumption data described in Chatterjee and Hadi (2012), which is also referred in KKH(2023).

1.1 Description of the dataset:

  • The gasoline consumption data (Y) in Motor Trend magazine for the year 1975.
  • Source: Chatterjee and Hadi (2012) (Tables 9.16-9.17, pp255-256).
  • The data is collected on 30 models of cars to study the factors that determine the gasoline consumption of cars.
The gasoline consumption data (Case 3). Chatterjee and Hadi (2012)
- K = 11, N = 30
- Y   Miles/gallon  
- X2    Displacement (cubic inches)
- X3    Horsepower (feet/pound) 
- X4    Torque (feet/pound)
- X5    Compression ratio   
- X6    Rear axle ratio
- X7    Carburetor (barrels)    
- X8    No. of transmission speeds
- X9    Overall length (inches) 
- X10   Width (inches)
- X11   Weight (pounds) 
- X12   Transmission type (1:automatic, 0:manual)

2 Conducting the EEM-M

The Empirically Effective Modelling methodology, or EEM-M, is proposed and developed in KKH (2024). It consists of two parts, XMSP and yMSP. There are two main functions, setenv_eem() and run_eem(), for that perticular purpose. In what follows, we are going to explain them.

Remarks about notation adopted and setups prepared in the program.

  • \(\tau\): index that differentiates models (sets of explanatory variables) of the same model size
  • \(J\): index that differentiate model sizes (number of explantory variables in a single model)
  • The original explanatory variable matrix \(X\) has the column index number starting from 1: \(1,2,...,J\). This contrasts to KKH (24) that runs through \(2,...,J\).
  • The Post I-control can be executed after the VR / VI algorithm is done, which is not explicitly described in KKH (24). Note that the Pre I-control is prioritized when both Pre and Post are set to run.
  • As alternatives of the model selection criterion in yMSP, AIC, BIC, adjusted \(R^2\) are provided.

2.1 The function setenv_eem()

  • The function setenv_eem() must be executed prior to the main function run_eem(), except when all the default values are used in run_eem().
  • It returns a list of the parameters that control computation and outputs made in run_eem(). The returned value shall be specified in the argument params in the subsequent run_eem().

The list of parameters that can be set in setenv_eem, along with their respective default values.

# algorithm to be adopted
- algo = "VR",  # "VI" 
# process control
- pca_VR = T,　# for VR only
- pre_Ictrl = T,
- post_Ictrl = F,
- do_yMSP = T,
# thresholds
- a_th = 0.9, # PC loading correlation. Ignored if pca_VR = F
- b_th = 0.4, # PCA relative contribution. Ignored if pca_VR = F
- cq_th = 0.95, # I-control
- dR_th = 0.9, # C-control
# output control
- keep_history = F,
- comp_ICRI = T
- prt_ext = T
- prt_progress = F,
- prt_details = F,
- write_output = T,
- output_id = "eem",
- output_path = "./out",
# criterion for yMSP
- ymsp_criteria = "AIC" # "BIC", "aR2",
# misc
- rm_rdn_ApwJp = "smaller" # "larger", "equiv"
- rm_rdn_VR = "none" # "smaller", "larger"
- rm_rdn_post_Ictrl = "none" # "smaller", "larger"
- nmod_max = 100 # upper limit allowed for cumulative models in the VI iteration

2.2 The function run_eem()

  • This function executes XMSP and produce various outputs.
  • It also execute yMSP if do_yMSP is TRUE, under which case the parameter ymsp_criteria specified in setenv_eem() is used to select the best OLS model.
  • It returns a list of the outputs about selected models and accompanying information about the selection process.
  • The explanatory variables x, as a matrix or a data.frame, and the response variable y must be provided as the first two arguments of the function.
  • The third argument params must be provided as an output of setenv_eem(), except when the default parameter values are used altogher, in which case, the argument can be omitted.
Usage:
# Example 1
# Select the VI algorithm for XMSP, as well as BIC as the criterion for yMSP
pars1 <- setenv_eem(algo = "VI", ymsp_criteria = "BIC")
output1 <- run_eem(Xmat, Yvec, params = pars1)
#
# Example 2
# Select the VR algorithm (default) for XMSP, with no pre I-control, with no yMSP
pars2 <- setenv_eem(pre_Ictrl = F, do_ySMP = F) 
output2 <- run_eem(Xmat, Yvec, params = pars2)
#
# Example 3
# Use the all default values of parameters
# Select the VI algorithm for XMSP, as well as BIC as the criterion for yMSP
output3 <- run_eem(Xmat, Yvec)
  • Outputs of run_xmsp: a list of elements including, but not limited to:
- summary: storing the most important results
  - xlab_initial
  - xlab_selected
  - n_models_selected_total
  - coef_best_model: Regression coefficients of the best model selected by yMSP with the chosen selection criterion ymsp_criteria
  - fit_best_model: The accompanying fit measures, together with the "risk measures" of the model prposed in KKH (24)
- xidx_selected: models (sets of variables) by XSMP. A list, each element of which has a data.frame object containing a set of variable indices (of the same length) selected by XMSP. The List of structure is used to differentiate model sizes, or the number of variables (index $J$) - xindices: various indices of each of selected models by XMSP
- status: record of the execution status of each step consisting of EEM-M
- params: parameters for the execution
- result_preIctrl: result of the pre I-control
- result_Cctrl: result of C-control
- result_ymsp: result of yMSP
- Xmat: explanatory data matrix $X(0)$
- y: response variable vector

2.2.1 Example 1: VI algorithm

  • Setting for computation
    • The XMSP algorithm: “VI”
    • Pre I-control: TRUE, Threshold: \(c_q=0.9\)
    • Threshold for VI: \(d_R=0.95\)
    • Post I-control: FALSE
    • Model selection criterion for yMSP = adjusted \(R^2\)
pars1 <- setenv_eem(algo = "VI", dR_th = 0.95, cq_th = 0.90, 
             pre_Ictrl = T, post_Ictrl = F, prt_msgs = F,
             output_path = "results", ymsp_criteria = "aR2") 
output1 <- run_eem(Xmat, Y_vec, params = pars1)
  • Detailed contents of the output of run_eem():
    • Refer to the Appendix.

2.2.2 Example 2: VR algorithm

  • Setting for computation
    • The XMSP algorithm: “VR”
    • Pre I-control: FALSE
    • PCA: TRUE. \(a=0.9, b=0.4\) (default)
    • Threshold for VR: \(d_R=0.95\)
    • Post I-control: TRUE. Threshold \(c_q=0.94\)
# setup parameters
pars2 <- setenv_eem(algo = "VR", 
                    a_th = 0.9, b_th = 0.4,
                    dR_th = 0.95, cq_th = 0.94,
             pre_Ictrl = F, post_Ictrl = T, prt_msgs = F,
             output_path = "results") 
# run EEM, i.e., XMSP and yMSP together
output2 <- run_eem(Xmat, Y_vec, params = pars2)

2.3 Other useful functions: run_xmsp, run_ymsp

Instead of running run_eem(), you can utilize either run_xmsp() and/or run_ymsp() that specifically conduct XMSP and yMSP respectively both of which comprise the whole EEM-M. In fact, run_eem() is nothing more than a wrapper function of the two, so essentially the outputs altogether can essentially be equvalent to that from run_eem().

In run_xmsp(), OLS regression is conducted for each of selected models (or sets of explanatory variables) produced by the preceding XMSP with run_xmsp(). There, the best model will be selected in light of the model criterion, currently either one of AIC, BIC, or Adjusted \(R^2\). In order to run seemlessly between the two steps, the latter run_ymsp shall only accept outputs from run_xmsp().

run_xmsp(x, 
         params = setenv_eem())
- x: a matrix or data frame of explantory variables
- params: an output object of <tt>setenv_eem()</tt>. A list of parameter values specified for yMSP.
run_ymsp(y, 
         output_of_XMSP,
         params = setenv_eem())
- y: a response variable (vector)
- output_of_XMPS: an output object of <tt>run_xmsp()</tt>
- params: an output object of <tt>setenv_eem()</tt>. A list of parameter values specified for yMSP.

2.3.1 Example 3 (Example illustrated in 5.2 of KKH(23))

  • Setting for computation
    • The XMSP algorithm: VR
    • Pre I-control: Yes. Threshold: \(c_q=0.9\)
    • PCA: TRUE. \(a=0.9, b=0.4\) (default)
    • Threshold for VR: \(d_R=0.9\)
    • Post I-control: No
    • Model selection criterion for yMSP: AIC
pars3 <- setenv_eem(algo = "VR", 
        pca_VR = T,
        pre_Ictrl = T, 
        post_Ictrl = F,
        do_yMSP = F,
        cq_th = 0.9, dR_th = 0.9,
        a_th = 0.9, b_th = 0.4,
        comp_ICRI = T,
        write_output = T,
        prt_msgs = F,
        output_id = "eem_eg3",
        output_path = "./results",
        ymsp_criteria = "AIC"
        )

# Execution of XMSP
out3_xmsp <- run_xmsp(Xmat, params = pars3)

# Execution of yMSP
out3_ymsp <- run_ymsp(Y_vec, out3_xmsp, params = pars3)

3 Utilization of the obtained results for further analysis

Output objects obtained from run_eem(), as well as run_xmsp(), run_ymsp(), can be recycled for further analysis in R and elsewhere.

3.1 Combining results of yMSP with standard regression results

Here, we recycle results of XMSP in Examples 1 and 2 above. 

# Best fitted model in light of AIC (indices)
mod1 <- output1$summary$xidx_best_model %>% unlist()
yxdf1 <- data.frame(y = Y_vec, Xmat[, mod1, drop = F])
lm_mod1 <- lm(y ~ ., data = yxdf1)

mod2 <- output2$summary$xidx_best_model %>% unlist()
yxdf2 <- data.frame(y = Y_vec, Xmat[, mod2, drop = F])
lm_mod2 <- lm(y ~ ., data = yxdf2)

As references, here we run standard regressions (OLS regression without variable selection, and stepwise regression). - Full model (OLS regression without variable selection)

  • Stepwise regression

We aggregate all the results by using stargazer():

stargazer(res_ols, res_step, lm_mod1, lm_mod2,
          type = "text", # "html"
          digits = 3, digits.extra = 1, align = TRUE,
          report = "vct*",
          df = FALSE,
          dep.var.caption = 'Best model for',
          dep.var.labels = "", #NULL, #'Vote share (%)',
          model.numbers = F,
          title = 'Best models VI vs VR',
          column.labels = c("OLS", "Stepwise", "VI", "VR"),

)

  geom_point(aes(colour = Hbar)) +
  geom_label(aes(label = ID, hjust = 0.5, vjust = 0)) +
  labs(title = paste0("cMXK vs dMXK for all selected models"))

3.3 Storing the key outputs as text files

By setting the argument write_output == T in setenv_eem(), the model selection results can be stored as text files. You can change the prefix of output file names (default value: “eem”)

Outputs of XMSP

Three types of text files will be produced. Each has a distinct format, but carry the same content as a whole. Here, described in the case of algo = “VR”, However, it is essentially the same for “VI”.

  • Format 1: “eem_VR_J[n]_index.csv” ([n] contains index number that runs in VI or VI.) (Store the index of each variable in one model as an integer in a separate cell. Since the number of variables used depends on the size of J, the variables are to be stored in separate files for each size of J.)
  • Format 2: “eem_VR_label.csv” (All variable labels in one model are stored in one cell as comma “,” as a delimitor)
  • Format 3: “eem_VR_matrix.csv” (Matrix format in which each variable is arranged in columns and each model in rows, with 1 in the cell position corresponding to the variable selected in the model and missing values in all other positions.)

Outputs of yMSP

Among ouput lists in run_ymsp() and run_eem(), the regression coefficients and their various indices in the best fitted model (summary$coef_best_model), as well as its various model fit measures (summary$fit_best_model) will be stored as text files.

  • Default file name: “eem_VR_ymsp.txt”
